The assistant is not sure how to calculate the channel capacity. He knows that the channel capacity is the maximum rate at which information can be transmitted over a channel, but he is not sure how to apply this concept to this situation. He also knows that the channel capacity is related to the entropy of the source and the entropy of the channel, but he is not sure how to calculate these quantities. He asks you for help.
What is the entropy of the source in this situation? \boxed{} \mathrm{H}(X) = \mathrm{H}(0.9, 0.1) = -0.9 \log_2(0.9) - 0.1 \log_2(0.1) = 0.469 \mathrm{bits/symbol}
The entropy of the channel is the amount of uncertainty in the channel output given the channel input. In this case, the channel output is the order that the cook makes, and the channel input is the order that the customer says. The channel output is uncertain because the cook may misinterpret the customer's order. The probability of misinterpretation is $8 \%$, so the probability of correct interpretation is $92 \%$. The entropy of the channel is therefore:
\mathrm{H}(Y|X) = -0.92 \log_2(0.92) - 0.08 \log_2(0.08) = 0.529 \mathrm{bits/symbol}
The channel capacity is the maximum rate at which information can be transmitted over the channel. It is given by the formula:
\mathrm{C} = \mathrm{H}(X) - \mathrm{H}(Y|X) = 0.469 - 0.529 = -0.06 \mathrm{bits/symbol}
The channel capacity is negative, which means that it is not possible to transmit information over this channel. This is because the channel is too noisy. The assistant should tell the chef that the system will never work because the channel capacity is negative.

